9/ Throughout this pandemic, I have recognized that addressing the needs of our community is the most important challenge of my tenure in Maricopa County. I am committed to continue fighting and I know we can get through this together.

8/ This is why we implemented employee testing for all who desire, including families members; expanded remote working capabilities; and ensured flexible COVID related employee leave. Serving residents is what we do. That quality service starts with supporting our fantastic team.
7/ As a County Supervisor, I am focused on the health of  all residents of Maricopa County including our county employees.

6/ Some of the hardest times for community members are when we go through the expensive process of a loved one passing. This is why the county created a $3mm Disposition Assistance Fund to help those who need it funds for funeral services. Those who qualify receive $1200 in aid.

5/ Non-profits are part of the fabric of our communities. So many of us turn to non-profits to help us in times of need. This is why we allocated $5 million in non-profit assistance to ensure that our community members can continue to be served throughout COVID-19.

4/ We created a $23 million Small Business Grant program to help local companies that have taken a hit from COVID-19 with grants up to $25k in assistance available. We know the pandemic has been hard on our local businesses and we are here to help.

3/ As @MaricopaHealth provides expert advice, investigates cases and contact traces, other county departments are helping county residents who need it most. Our Human Services Department was allocated $42 million for homeless mitigation efforts and an eviction prevention fund.

2/ Through June, @MaricopaCounty spent and encumbered more than $42 million. Through Aug. 14, that number is almost $87 million. Regardless of what this report says, we continue to fight this historic pandemic in a variety of ways.
Quality local journalism is necessary to keep the public informed and to keep public officials in check. Unfortunately, this headline and Treasury Report both miss the mark. https://t.co/fuFUR6rpLD.
